WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.132 --> 00:00:04.885
Interviewer: I'm here with Marcos.
What is this an experiment we're doing?

00:00:04.885 --> 00:00:06.349
I was like hey instead
of having pictures on our

00:00:06.349 --> 00:00:07.905
website, maybe we should
have videos of people.

00:00:07.905 --> 00:00:09.048
Marcos: Nice. Nice.

00:00:09.048 --> 00:00:10.221
Interviewer: So, what do you do here?

00:00:10.221 --> 00:00:11.844
Marcos: I'm a designer
here at the Khan Academy.

00:00:11.844 --> 00:00:14.354
That actually goes two different ways.

00:00:14.354 --> 00:00:16.466
One, I'm kind of doing
my software design, and

00:00:16.466 --> 00:00:19.138
that's kind of touching on the
exercise framework that we have.

00:00:19.138 --> 00:00:21.724
Right now I've been focused
a lot on trying to make

00:00:21.724 --> 00:00:23.810
more interactive exercises
easier to develop.

00:00:23.810 --> 00:00:26.429
There's a framework that
I'm building for that

00:00:26.429 --> 00:00:28.218
I'm [open sourcing] at the same time.

00:00:28.218 --> 00:00:30.639
Interviewer: What do you mean
by more interactive exercise?

00:00:30.639 --> 00:00:33.935
Marcos: Right now a lot of
our exercises present to you

00:00:33.935 --> 00:00:36.809
with a question. It's like, what
is the sum of blah blah blah?

00:00:36.839 --> 00:00:39.839
Or, complete the square.
It ask you this very simple

00:00:39.839 --> 00:00:42.954
one step computation. A lot
of stuff that I'm looking at

00:00:42.954 --> 00:00:44.744
is how do you make exercises
that let you follow

00:00:44.744 --> 00:00:47.959
a larger kind of narrative
of problem solving.

00:00:47.959 --> 00:00:50.741
In that case it would be
like, let's say you are

00:00:50.741 --> 00:00:53.189
this tall here, and your
shadow is this feet long.

00:00:53.189 --> 00:00:57.652
Your friend is over, maybe,
35 nautical miles away, and

00:00:57.652 --> 00:01:01.528
his shadow is this long.
Giving that what do you

00:01:01.528 --> 00:01:03.104
expect the circumference
of the earth to be?

00:01:03.104 --> 00:01:03.784
Interviewer: Oh yeah.

00:01:03.784 --> 00:01:06.654
Marcos: You're recreating like
the greatest ... doing all the

00:01:06.654 --> 00:01:10.704
scientific discoveries.
Their not very hard if

00:01:10.704 --> 00:01:12.490
you know the basic concepts in there.

00:01:12.490 --> 00:01:14.870
You just need someone to
guide you along the way.

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:17.882
A lot of what I've been
thinking about is developing

00:01:17.882 --> 00:01:19.915
a framework and actually
developing a framework

00:01:19.915 --> 00:01:20.948
not just thinking about it.

00:01:20.948 --> 00:01:21.859
Interviewer: Right. Right.

00:01:21.859 --> 00:01:22.915
Marcos: For making that happen.

00:01:22.915 --> 00:01:25.373
Interviewer: You'r background
is pretty interesting.

00:01:25.373 --> 00:01:28.848
You started off at MIT. CS major?

00:01:28.848 --> 00:01:30.537
Marcos: Math with CS.

00:01:30.537 --> 00:01:31.261
Interviewer: Math with CS.

00:01:31.261 --> 00:01:32.836
Marcos: People call it diet 6.

00:01:32.836 --> 00:01:35.895
Interviewer: Diet 6. 6 is
of course computer science.

00:01:35.895 --> 00:01:37.237
Marcos: 6 is computer science.

00:01:37.237 --> 00:01:39.928
Interviewer: It's kind of the math
... computer science really is math.

00:01:39.928 --> 00:01:45.504
Then you decided that that was not enough.

00:01:45.504 --> 00:01:48.005
Marcos: I think I was pleasantly surprised

00:01:48.005 --> 00:01:50.453
with how that had gone.
What I was really focused

00:01:50.453 --> 00:01:53.079
on at the time was the
[unintelligible] in the context

00:01:53.079 --> 00:01:55.587
of making text books. Text
books [unintelligible]

00:01:55.587 --> 00:01:59.206
dining out or whatever. I
still believe. I want to

00:01:59.206 --> 00:02:00.921
make a really good text book.

00:02:00.921 --> 00:02:05.339
Interviewer: We got text books
here and some science books.

00:02:05.339 --> 00:02:07.604
Marcos: I actually ended
up doing after teaching

00:02:07.604 --> 00:02:10.630
