00:09:05.399 --> 00:09:06.696
Interviewer: Do things that
text books couldn't do?

00:09:06.696 --> 00:09:08.604
Marcos: I think text books
are capable of a lot.

00:09:08.604 --> 00:09:11.927
I'll be honest. Maybe
we disagree. (laughing)

00:09:11.927 --> 00:09:13.777
Interviewer: (laughing) No. No.

00:09:13.777 --> 00:09:16.892
Marcos: I firmly in the
power of the text book.

00:09:16.892 --> 00:09:20.146
I think for the things
that ... for the reactive

00:09:20.146 --> 00:09:22.788
exercises we can pull
off and for the ability

00:09:22.788 --> 00:09:26.144
to ask questions that are experimentally.

00:09:26.144 --> 00:09:29.678
You can place a little
experimental test bed

00:09:29.678 --> 00:09:32.748
in one of these exercises,
and I think that's powerful.

00:09:32.748 --> 00:09:35.761
I think it's huge right,
being able to see a whole.

00:09:35.761 --> 00:09:38.624
I got the answer. What
happens if I have done this.

00:09:38.624 --> 00:09:42.402
Seeing that there's an
exercise that is able to

00:09:42.402 --> 00:09:44.231
adapt to that way of
thinking. I think that's huge.

00:09:44.231 --> 00:09:46.698
Interviewer: Right. That
would have been hard

00:09:46.698 --> 00:09:47.942
with a traditional text book.

00:09:47.942 --> 00:09:51.988
Marcos: Yeah. You end up having
to build this scalpelling,

00:09:51.988 --> 00:09:55.275
basically in paper, which
again totally fine. Right.

00:09:55.275 --> 00:09:58.850
It's the time you can loose
being unable to explore

00:09:58.850 --> 00:10:01.781
